==Summary==

Replace the legacy <code>digibyte.org</code> codebase with a dark-only,
blue-only, dependency-free static site featuring live chain telemetry,
36-locale parity, and Lighthouse 95/86/100/100 — positioned as a community
growth and developer-acquisition funnel rather than a brochure refresh.

==Abstract==

This Informational DIP proposes a complete visual and technical redesign
of <code>https://digibyte.org/</code> (repository:
[https://github.com/DigiByte-Core/DGBio DGBio]). The redesign replaces a
legacy jQuery + nine-plugin stack with a dependency-free vanilla
ES-module implementation, removes a partially-themed light mode in
favour of a consistent dark experience, introduces live on-chain
telemetry from public DigiByte explorer APIs, and lifts Lighthouse
scores from 56/78/73/92 to 95/86/100/100.

Because <code>digibyte.org</code> is the project's primary onboarding
surface for users, developers, exchanges and journalists, the proposal
is positioned as a community-growth and developer-acquisition
initiative: live block height, hashrate and price answer the implicit
"is this project still active?" question on first viewport, while a
DevHub section with copy-pasteable API examples and a zero-build static
architecture lower the barrier for new front-end contributors who
historically become Core contributors. The DIP does not affect
consensus, P2P, RPC or wallet behaviour and is therefore Informational.

Discussion of this DIP takes place in the
[https://github.com/DigiByte-Core/dips/discussions/categories/dip-discussions
DIP discussion forum] prior to PR submission, per DIP-0001.

==Why a DIP and not just a pull request?==

DIP-0001 notes that small per-project patches typically do not require a
DIP. This proposal is intentionally scoped beyond a single patch:

* It establishes a '''brand and design direction''' (blue-only palette,
  dark-only theme, isometric blockchain visual language) that is intended
  to outlive any specific implementation and bind future site maintainers.
* It defines a '''site contribution workflow''' (zero-build static, locale
  sync tool, PR-based deployment) that future maintainers should preserve.
* It commits to '''measurable success criteria''' that the community can
  evaluate, rather than relying on a single maintainer's judgement.
* It is the first proposal in a planned '''website-DIP track''' covering
  follow-up topics such as analytics platform migration and a first-party
  DigiAssets explorer.

For these reasons the proposal is submitted as an Informational DIP for
community ratification, not as a solo maintainer merge.

